            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Joshua Kaplan\u2019s story began not in the digital ether, but in the sun-drenched suburbs of Palo Alto. Raised by two Stanford academics\u2014a history professor father and a linguist mother\u2014his childhood was filled with books, intellectual debate, and the quiet expectation of a traditional scholarly path. However, growing up in the 80s, he was captivated by the nascent digital frontier, seeing the artistic potential in the glowing pixels of early computer screens.\n\nRejecting a future in the humanities, Joshua pursued an MFA in Digital Media Arts from San Jose State University in the early 90s, a move his parents found baffling. He saw technology not as a tool for business, but as a new artistic medium. He rode the first dot-com wave, working on experimental websites and interactive CD-ROMs, and survived its spectacular crash with a hardened sense of pragmatism. This crucible transformed him from a hands-on digital artist into a leader who could shepherd chaotic, creative projects to completion. Now, as an Executive Producer, he orchestrates large-scale immersive experiences, blending art, code, and sensory design for high-end restaurants, pop-up museums, and entertainment venues.\n\nA key turning point was an amicable but draining divorce in his late forties, which prompted him to re-evaluate his life. He shed the pretenses of a Silicon Valley power couple and embraced a more authentic existence. His social life now revolves around a tight-knit group of fellow Gen X creatives and tech veterans who share his history of the Bay Area\u2019s evolution.\n\nHis current life is a study in controlled balance. Mornings begin with coffee on the deck of his Noe Valley flat, followed by a 3.5-mile electric bike ride to his SoMa studio, a commute he cherishes as his daily meditation. He loves the contrast between Noe Valley\u2019s quiet, village-like atmosphere and the industrial-creative buzz of his workplace. At 54, Joshua isn't chasing a bigger paycheck. His dream is to create a legacy project: a permanent, city-defining immersive installation that transcends entertainment to become a beloved piece of public art, forever weaving his artistic vision into the fabric of the city that shaped him."
